 To generate a table of contents automatically in a LATEX document, we need to use the `\tableofcontents` command. This command is usually placed just after the document's title and before the main content.

Here is an example of a LATEX document with a table of contents:

```latex
\documentclass{article}

\begin{document}

\title{My Document}
\author{John Doe}
\date{\today}

\maketitle

\tableofcontents

\section{Introduction}
This is the introduction section.

\section{Conclusion}
This is the conclusion section.

\end{document}
```

In this example, the `\tableofcontents` command is placed after the title and before the main content. The table of contents will list all sections in the document.

To generate a table of contents for a specific section, we can use the `\addcontentsline` command:

```latex
\documentclass{article}

\begin{document}

\title{My Document}
\author{John Doe}
\date{\today}

\maketitle

\tableofcontents

\section{Introduction}
This is the introduction section.

\section{Conclusion}
This is the conclusion section.

\addcontentsline{toc}{part}{My Part}
\section{My Section}
This is my section.

\end{document}
```

In this example, the `\addcontentsline` command is used to add a new part to the table of contents. The `part` option specifies that this is a part, and `My Part` is the title of the part. The `\section` command following the `\addcontentsline` command will be included in this part.

 To draw a chessboard from a FEN notation in LaTeX, you can use the `chessboard` package. Here's an example of how to use it:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{chessboard}

\begin{document}

\begin{chessboard}[setboard="rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 1"]
\chessboardoutput
\end{chessboard}

\end{document}
```

In this example, the `setboard` option is used to specify the FEN notation of the chessboard state. The `chessboardoutput` command generates the chessboard.

The FEN notation in this example represents a standard starting position of a chess game. The `w` at the end indicates that White moves first (`KQkq` represents the starting position from Black's perspective).

Please note that the `chessboard` package requires the `pgf` or `tikz` package to work. If you don't have it installed, you can add it to the preamble:

```latex
\usepackage{pgf} % or \usepackage{tikz}
```

Also, you need to compile your document with `XeLaTeX` or `LuaLaTeX` since the `chessboard` package uses Unicode characters for the chess pieces.

